SIMPLE: plumb
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plumb
<hw>Plumb</hw> <pr>(pl⟦ucr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>plomb</ets>, L. <ets>plumbum</ets> lead, a leaden ball or bullet;
cf. Gr. <grk>mo`lybos</grk>, <grk>mo`libos</grk>, <grk>mo`lybdos</grk>.
Cf. <er>Plummet</er>, <er>Plunge</er>.]</ety> <def>A little mass or
weight of lead, or the like, attached to a line, and used by builders,
etc., to indicate a vertical direction; a plummet; a plumb bob. See
<cref>Plumb line</cref>, below.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Plumb bob</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Bob</er>, 4.</cd> --
<col><b>Plumb joint</b></col>, <cd>in sheet-metal work, a lap joint,
fastened by solder.</cd> -- <col><b>Plumb level</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Level</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Plumb line</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>The cord by which a plumb bob is suspended; a plummet</cd>.
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A line directed to the center of gravity of the
earth.</cd> -- <col><b>Plumb rule</b></col>, <cd>a narrow board with a
plumb line, used by builders and carpenters.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plumb</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plumb
<hw>Plumb</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Perpendicular; vertical; conforming
the direction of a line attached to a plumb; <as>as, the wall is
<ex>plumb</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plumb</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Plumb
<hw>Plumb</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a plumb direction;
perpendicularly.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Plumb</xex> down he falls.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plumb</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Plumb
<hw>Plumb</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Plumbed</conjf> <pr>(pl⟦ucr⟧md)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Plumbing</conjf> <pr>(pl⟦ucr⟧m"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To adjust by a plumb line; to cause to be
perpendicular; <as>as, to <ex>plumb</ex> a building or a
wall</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To sound with a plumb or plummet, as the depth of
water; hence, to examine by test; to ascertain the depth, quality,
dimension, etc.; to sound; to fathom; to test.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He did not attempt to <qex>plumb</qex> his intellect.</q>
<rj><qau>Ld. Lytton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To seal with lead; <as>as, to <ex>plumb</ex> a
drainpipe</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To supply, as a building, with a system of
plumbing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plumbage</ent>⟦br⟧
